[1] Norovirus, restaurant - USA (Colorado)
Date: Fri 18 Jun 2004
From: C.H. Calisher <calisher@ cybercell.net>
Source: Associated Press report, Fri 18 Jun 2004 [edited]

USA: Restaurant-associated Suspected Norovirus Outbreak in Colorado
--------------------------------------------------
More than 240 people have contacted health officials in the past 2 days to
complain they became ill after eating at a Fort Collins restaurant. The
outbreak is so large that 10 Larimer County employees have been assigned to
the investigation of what happened at the Texas Roadhouse, part of a
national chain based in Louisville, Ky. The restaurant has been closed
temporarily, and the company has hired a private contractor to disinfect
the restaurant, health officials said on Thu 17 Jun 2004. People who ate at
the popular steak house say they experienced cramps, nausea, chills,
diarrhea, vomiting and other symptoms within 48 hours of their meals. Some
were treated at Poudre Valley Hospital, said Ann Watson, spokeswoman for
the county health department.
In 2003, the restaurant was rated "good" in food inspections. In 2002, it
was declared "excellent," according to county records. The problems appear
to involve people who ate at the restaurant Saturday, Sunday, and Monday,
said Ed Shemm, the county's assistant director of environmental health.
Health investigators are asking people what they ate and when they ate it
and have taken samples from people for testing. Based on interviews,
officials say the virus appears to be a norovirus, which is fairly common
and easily transmitted, Shemm said.
--
C.H. Calisher
<calisher@ cybercell.net>
