[2] Norovirus, restaurant - USA (Colorado)
Date: Sat 19 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Fort Collins Coloradoan, Sat 19 Jun 2004 [edited]
<http://www.coloradoan.com/news/stories/20040619/news/679364.html>

USA: Norovirus Outbreak Closes Restaurant in Colorado
-----------------------------------------------------
The Texas Roadhouse [in Fort Collins, Colorado] reopened on Fri 18 Jun
2004, 2 days after it shut down for "top-to-bottom" cleaning in the wake of
viral outbreak like none ever witnessed by the chain. Larimer County health
officials say about 270 people complained of [having been affected by
severe viral gastroenteritis virus] on Sunday and Monday after eating at
the Fort Collins steak house on Sat 12 Jun 2004.
County health officials confirmed that norovirus infection was responsible
for the outbreak: [confirmatory results] were returned by the state's
health department Friday. Noroviruses have been linked to massive outbreaks
[of viral gastroenteritis] on cruise ships and are spread easily,
especially by people who fail to wash their hands after using the bathroom.
The viruses can be transmitted to other people and surfaces, such as
plates, glasses and silverware. Restaurant officials, who said as many as
20 employees might have had the illness, are not exactly sure how the
outbreak began.
When asked why the restaurant waited until Wednesday to close, even though
county officials investigated the outbreak on Monday and Tuesday, Hart said
the county had given the restaurant the OK to continue serving food. He
added that noroviruses are especially difficult to control, but pointed to
Texas Roadhouse's recent food-safety inspections -- "good" last year and
"excellent" in 2003 -- as an indicator of the restaurant's commitment to
cleanliness. County health workers are entering information into a computer
database that could yield more specific information about the outbreak's
origin, but data wasn't available Friday.
The symptoms of norovirus illness usually include nausea, vomiting,
diarrhea, and some stomach cramping. Sometimes people additionally have a
low-grade fever, chills, headache, muscle aches, and a general sense of
tiredness. The illness often begins suddenly, and the infected person might
feel very sick. The illness is usually brief, with symptoms lasting only
about one or 2 days. In general, children experience more vomiting than
adults. Most people with norovirus illness have both symptoms.
[Byline: Michael De Yoanna]
