[3] Norovirus, institutions - Australia (New South Wales): suspected
Date: 23 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Cowra Guardian, Wed 23 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://cowra.yourguide.com.au/detail.asp?class=news&subclass=local&category=general%20news&story_id=315741&y=2004&m=6>

Australia (NSW): Institution in Quarantine Following Gastroenteritis Outbreak
---------------------------------------------------
Bilyara is under strict quarantine due to an outbreak of [viral]
gastroenteritis, a common but highly infectious condition affecting the
stomach and intestines that results in vomiting and diarrhoea. Bilyara
administrator Ray Harris said the outbreak began with several cases late
last week and grew to 16 cases by yesterday, precipitating the decision to
quarantine the village [location of a health-care institution?]. Access to
Bilyara is restricted to essential services only, with general visitors
unable to access the Centre. This weekend's Salvation Army fashion parade
at Bilyara has also been cancelled. Mr Harris said he had notified the
Public Health Unit as required and staff were taking all necessary precautions.
Gastroenteritis has appeared at other regional institutions, including
Canowindra, Molong and as many as 300 cases in Dubbo.
The main symptoms of viral gastroenteritis are vomiting and watery
diarrhoea, though other symptoms may include nausea, fever, abdominal pain,
headache, and muscle aches. There is no specific treatment for viral
gastroenteritis except rest and drinking plenty of fluids, and most people
recover without any complications.
